step.tex:
\begin{align}
I &= \int\dfrac{3}{4}\sin (2x+1)dx - \int\dfrac{1}{4}\sin 3 (2x +1)dx\\
&= \dfrac{3}{4} \int sin(2x+1) dx - \dfrac{1}{4}\int  \sin(6x+3) dx \\
&= -\dfrac{3}{8}\cos (2x + 1) + \dfrac{1}{24} \cos (6 x + 3) + C
\end{align}

\begin{align}
I &= \int\dfrac{3}{4}\sin (2x+1)dx - \int\dfrac{1}{4}\sin 3 (2x +1)dx\\
&= \dfrac{3}{4} \int sin(2x+1) dx - \dfrac{1}{4}\int  \sin(6x+3) dx \\
&= \dfrac{3}{8}\cos (2x + 1) - \dfrac{1}{24} \cos (6 x + 3) + C
\end{align}

step.reason:
\int \sin (a x)dx = -\dfrac{\cos (a x)}{a}+ C_1. \text{ Alternatively} \\
\begin{align}
\sin^3 x = \sin^2 x \cdot \sin x  \text{ which results in}\\
-\dfrac{1}{2} \cos (2x +1) + \dfrac{1}{6} \cos^3 (2x+1) + C
\end{align}\\
\text{Both are equivalent.}
